  <h1>Classeq Commercial Dishwasher Repair — Los Angeles &amp; Southern California</h1>

  <p>Classeq is a British commercial warewashing brand — they're based in Milton Keynes, England, and part of ITW (Illinois Tool Works), the same corporate family that owns Hobart and Jackson. Their G series glasswashers dominate the UK pub and bar market the way Jackson's TempStar dominates the US cocktail bar segment. In LA, Classeq equipment shows up in British-managed hospitality operations — English pub-style bars on the Westside, UK restaurant groups that opened LA locations and spec'd their standard UK equipment, and British hotel management companies that run SoCal properties. West Hollywood and Santa Monica have enough British-connected hospitality that Classeq isn't a rare find in our service territory.</p>

  <p>The Classeq-specific service challenge in LA is the same as for Washtech: the brand isn't in the American commercial service training ecosystem. Most US commercial appliance companies have never worked on one. We service Classeq throughout SoCal — call <strong>{phone}</strong> and describe your model, and we'll confirm same-day availability. $120 commercial diagnostic applied to the repair.</p>

  <h2>Classeq Equipment We Service</h2>

  <h3>G Series — Glasswashers</h3>
  <p>The Classeq G400 and G500 are their core glasswashers — compact undercounter machines built specifically for bar glasswashing throughput. The G400 is the standard single-pump model; the G400DUO and G500DUO add a second wash pump for higher pressure and throughput, which makes them appropriate for high-volume bar operations. The DUO variant's dual-pump architecture means a pump failure presents differently than on a single-pump machine — one pump can partially compensate for the other, so the machine keeps running but at reduced wash quality before any fault indication appears. When we get a G400DUO or G500DUO call for declining wash quality with no error code, the dual-pump system is the first thing we check.</p>
  <p>In LA's hard water environment, the G series booster element and spray nozzles follow the same scale pattern as every other high-temp glasswasher in this market. Monthly descaling is appropriate. The G series also includes Classeq's water softener on some configurations — same maintenance requirement as Winterhalter and Meiko softeners: check salt level weekly, don't wait for the alarm.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> Classeq G400, G500, G400DUO, G500DUO</p>

  <h3>P Series — Undercounter Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>Classeq's P series undercounters — P450, P500, P500A, P500DUO, P500AWS, P500AD — are their full-size undercounter dishwasher range, stepping up from the glasswasher-focused G series to handle full dish loads. The P500AD and P500AWS include Classeq's auto-dose detergent and rinse aid system. When the auto-dose system drifts — same failure mode as Comenda's Auto Dose and Miele Professional's dosing system — dishes come out with residue or chemical film. We check dosing delivery rate on every P series call where wash quality is the complaint.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> Classeq P450, P500, P500A, P500DUO, P500AWS, P500AD</p>

  <h3>Hydro &amp; Duo Series — Mid-Volume</h3>
  <p>The Classeq Hydro 750, 850, and 1000 and the Duo 750, 850, and 1000 are Classeq's mid-volume hood-type and passthrough machines. Numbers indicate racks per hour capacity. These appear in British-managed restaurant kitchens and hotel dining operations in SoCal. The Hydro series is Classeq's energy-efficient line — lower water consumption per rack, which in LA's water-cost environment is a genuine operational advantage but also means scale concentrates faster in the smaller wash tank volume. Same tradeoff as Electrolux Professional's Green &amp; Clean and Blakeslee's Perfecta-Rinse in the SoCal market.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> Classeq Hydro 750, 850, 1000, Duo 750, 850, 1000</p>

  <h3>D500 — Door-Type</h3>
  <p>The Classeq D500 and D500DUO are their hood-type door machines for mid-volume operations — the British equivalent of a Hobart AM or Jackson RackStar 66. In LA, these appear in larger British-managed catering operations. Service follows standard door-type commercial dishwasher protocol with Classeq-specific additions: touch control panel diagnostics on current models require familiarity with Classeq's error code system, which uses a different fault display than American commercial dishwashers.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> Classeq D500, D500DUO</p>

  <h2>British Brand, American Market — The Parts Reality</h2>

  <p>Classeq is part of ITW — same parent as Hobart and Jackson. That corporate connection helps on parts: ITW's North American commercial parts network has some Classeq component availability through its broader distribution infrastructure. Common wear items — elements, pump assemblies, spray arm components, door switches — have reasonable sourcing timelines of 2–4 business days. Classeq-specific control components for touch panel models have longer lead times, and we'll tell you that on-site.</p>

  <p>What we've found in LA: most Classeq calls aren't control board issues. The G series and P series machines that appear in British-managed LA hospitality are typically failing for the same reasons every other high-temp commercial glasswasher fails in LA hard water: scaled booster elements, blocked spray nozzles, worn door switches, or softener salt neglect. These are serviceable same-day or next-day in almost every case.</p>

  <h2>Recent Classeq Service Calls</h2>

  <h3>"G500DUO glasswasher — glasses dirty, no fault code, West Hollywood bar"</h3>
  <p>British-managed bar near Santa Monica Blvd, Classeq G500DUO glasswasher producing inconsistently clean glasses — some loads fine, some with visible residue. No fault codes, machine cycling normally. The dual-pump system had one pump running at reduced flow — scale-restricted nozzles on the lower spray arm were limiting that pump's contribution while the upper pump was compensating. The inconsistency came from rack position: items over the working pump came out clean; items over the restricted pump came out with residue. Descaled both spray arm systems, cleaned the nozzles on the lower arm, verified balanced flow from both pumps. Problem resolved. The DUO's partial compensation is both a feature (keeps running) and a diagnostic challenge (no obvious fault).</p>

  <h3>"P500AD — auto-dose failure, chemical film, British restaurant Santa Monica"</h3>
  <p>UK restaurant group's LA location, Classeq P500AD, chef reported chemical film on crockery for two weeks. Auto-dose rinse aid pump had failed in overdose position — delivering approximately 3x spec dose per rack. Replaced the auto-dose pump assembly, calibrated delivery rate, ran test racks to verify clean output. Also found the booster element at about 60% of spec heat transfer due to scale — element wasn't failing but contributing to slower cycle times. Descaled while there. Chef said it was the first time the machine had run correctly in months.</p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <p><strong>Why is it so hard to find Classeq service in Los Angeles?</strong><br>
  Classeq is a British brand that's dominant in the UK bar and restaurant market but not widely known in the US commercial service industry. Most American commercial appliance companies haven't trained on Classeq equipment and don't stock parts. We service Classeq throughout SoCal — call {phone} and we'll confirm same-day availability for your model.</p>

  <p><strong>What is the Classeq DUO system on the G400DUO and G500DUO?</strong><br>
  DUO models use two independent wash pumps. This increases wash pressure and throughput compared to the single-pump G400/G500. The tradeoff for service: when one pump degrades from scale or wear, the other partially compensates, so the machine keeps running with declining wash quality before triggering a fault. We check both pump systems on every DUO call regardless of the stated complaint.</p>

  <p><strong>How often should Classeq equipment be descaled in Los Angeles?</strong><br>
  Monthly for glasswashers and undercounters; semi-annual for Hydro series heat exchangers. LA water at 250–350 ppm TDS is harder than UK water conditions for which Classeq's standard maintenance intervals are designed. Monthly descaling is the appropriate SoCal interval.</p>

  <p><strong>What is your diagnostic fee?</strong><br>
  $120 commercial diagnostic, applied to the repair when you proceed. On-site quote — what we quote is what's on the invoice.</p>

